In commit "validation: have LoadBlockIndex account for snapshot use" (dbca47ece6b9a3a5e02969270bfab340fce286c0)

I think I would suggest a few changes here:

- Consolidate the insert calls, and just focus on one case where blocks shouldn't be added instead of branching for other cases.
- Try to be less vague in comments ("fitting chainstates")
- Be a little more efficient avoiding the O(n) pindex call, and mention it explicitly in comment to be clear that it's intentional.

```diff
diff --git a/src/validation.cpp b/src/validation.cpp
index 4af1c7f07a0..eec27f63abb 100644
--- a/src/validation.cpp
+++ b/src/validation.cpp
@@ -3653,15 +3653,15 @@ bool BlockManager::LoadBlockIndex(
         if (pindex->IsAssumedValid() ||
                 (pindex->IsValid(BLOCK_VALID_TRANSACTIONS) &&
                  (pindex->HaveTxsDownloaded() || pindex->pprev == nullptr))) {
+            // Following call is O(n), but should not be a significant slowdown.
+            const bool has_assumed_valid_ancestors = pindex->reliesOnAssumedValid();
+
+            // Fill each chainstate's block candidate set. Add all blocks as
+            // candidates if the chainstate is allowed to rely on assumed-valid
+            // data. Otherwise avoid adding assumed-valid blocks so the
+            // chainstate will download and validate all earlier blocks.
             for (CChainState* chainstate : chainman.GetAll()) {
-                // Only add blocks which are assumed-valid to fitting chainstates, i.e. those
-                // populated on the basis of a UTXO snapshot.
-                if (pindex->reliesOnAssumedValid()) {
-                    if (chainstate->reliesOnAssumedValid()) {
-                        chainstate->setBlockIndexCandidates.insert(pindex);
-                    }
-                } else {
-                    // When blockindex doesn't rely on assumedvalid blocks, add it to all chainstates.
+                if (chainstate->reliesOnAssumedValid() || !has_assumed_valid_ancestors) {
                     chainstate->setBlockIndexCandidates.insert(pindex);
                 }
             }

```

Also it would be good to have unit test coverage for this

